TextEquiv.Unicode: to think, i. e. ponder. Cōgĭto, 1; mĕdĭtor, 1; consīdĕro, 1; i. e. to be of
opinion, existĭmo, 1; arbĭtror, 1; pŭto, 1; censeo, 2; ŏpīnor, 1.—To esteem
(a man of such and such a character), existĭmo, 1; dūco, 3; hăbeo, 2; (with
such words as magni, quanti, &c.) făcio, 3.—And do not think more of
your anger than of your character. Neu magis iræ vestræ quam famæ
consulatis. Sall.—And [saying] that they did not know up to that
time why they were thought enemies by the consul. Nec se ad id locorum
scire propter quam causam consuli pro hostibus fuerint. Liv.—Of which
matter I will write you word what I think. De quâ scribam ad te quod
thinness. Grăcĭlĭtas, tĕnuĭtas.—Of an assembly, infrĕquentia.
thirsty. Arĭdus; i. e. desirous of (in such phrases as bloodthirsty), ăvĭdus.
this. Hic, hicce (not poet., adding force to hic, Facc.).
thorough.—Plancius is a thorough friend of ours. Plancius totus noste
est. Cic.—A thorough and perfect general. Summus atque perfectus
thought. Cōgĭtatio, mĕdĭtatio, consĭdĕrātio.— Anxious thought, cura, sol-
lĭcĭtūdo; i. e. a thing thought of, a plan, consĭlium.—For there are
philosophers, and have been before, who believed that the gods took no
thought whatever of human affairs. Sunt enim philosophi et fuerunt qui
omnino nullam habere censerent humanarum rerum procurationem Deos.
Cic.— Others think that they do take thought for and provide for the
life of men. Alii censent ab iisdem vitæ hominum consuli et provideri. Cic.
thousand. Mille, indecl. in sing., in pl. millia -ium.
